sect2.para:
The Structured Clinical Interview for DSM-5 Disorders, Clinician Version (SCID-5-CV; First et al., 
            2016
         ) is a semi-structured clinical interview assessing for major diagnoses from the DSM-5. Anxiety disorders included in the SCID-5 include panic disorder, agoraphobia, social anxiety disorder, and GAD. The SCID-5 also screens for specific phobia and separation anxiety disorder, but further interviewing would be required to make a diagnosis of these disorders. The SCID-5 is an adaptive interview and can take between 30 min and 2 h depending on the number of symptoms the interviewee endorses. The SCID-5 has been found to have good clinical validity and satisfactory interrater reliability for anxiety disorders (Osório et al., 
            2019
         ).

The Diagnostic Interview for Anxiety, Mood, and OCD and Related Neuropsychiatric Disorders (DIAMOND) is a semi-structured clinical interview that assesses for anxiety, mood, somatic, obsessive-compulsive, trauma-related, feeding and eating, substance-related, and schizophrenia spectrum disorders (Tolin et al., 
            2016
         ). The anxiety disorder portion of the DIAMOND assesses for social anxiety disorder, panic disorder, agoraphobia, GAD, specific phobia, and separation anxiety disorder. The interview usually takes between 30 and 90 min. The DIAMOND has an optional self-report screening measure that can direct the clinician to which diagnoses are most relevant to the interviewee. The DIAMOND has been found to have very good to excellent interrater and test-retest reliability, and convergent validity with regard to other measures for anxiety disorders (Tolin et al., 
            2018
         ).

The Diagnostic Interview for Anxiety, Mood, and OCD and Related Neuropsychiatric Disorders: Child and Adolescent Version (DIAMOND-KID) is an adapted version of the DIAMOND
            DIAMOND
          for clients between the ages of 6 and 18 (Tolin et al., 
            2023a
         ). The DIAMOND-KID assesses for all the anxiety disorders included in the adult version along with selective mutism. The interrater reliability for GAD using the DIAMOND-KID was found to be questionable but was good to very good for social anxiety disorder and specific phobia (Tolin et al., 
            2023b
         ). The test-retest reliability for anxiety disorders was found to be very good to excellent along with showing good convergent validity (Tolin et al., 
            2023b
         ).

The Anxiety Disorder Interview Schedule for DSM-5 (ADIS-5) is a semi-structured clinical interview designed to diagnose current anxiety, mood, obsessive-compulsive, trauma, and related disorders based on DSM-5 criteria for the disorders (Brown & Barlow, 
            2014
         ). The ADIS-5 is designed to evaluate an individual for anxiety disorder but includes other disorders that may have similar presentations to assess for differential diagnosis. The ADIS-5 also includes a dimensional assessment of features and questions to prompt a functional analysis of most disorders. The ADIS-5 takes approximately 2 to 4 h to administer. The psychometric properties of the ADIS-5 have not been assessed, but the previous version of the measure (Anxiety Disorder Interview Schedule for DSM-IV) was found to have good to excellent interrater reliability.

The Mini International Neuropsychiatric Interview for DSM-5 (MINI-7) is a relatively short structured clinical interview assessing for the 17 most common psychiatric disorders from the DSM-III, DSM-IV, DSM-5, and ICD-10 (Sheehan et al., 
            1998
         ). Anxiety disorders assessed by the MINI-7 include panic disorder, agoraphobia, social anxiety disorder, and GAD. The MINI-7 takes about 15 to 20 min to administer. An earlier version of the MINI was found to have excellent interrater reliability, good test-retest reliability, and good convergent validity with other lengthier clinical interviews (Sheehan et al., 
            1998
         ). As a note, the use of the MINI-7 in clinical and research settings requires an approved license agreement with Dr. Sheehan directly.

The Mini International Neuropsychiatric Interview for Children and Adolescence (MINI Kid) assesses the 30 most common disorders or disorder subtypes in children (Sheehan et al., 
            2010
         ). The MINI Kid includes all anxiety disorders assessed by the adult version along with specific phobia and separation anxiety disorder. The MINI Kid was found to have substantial to excellent convergent validity and substantial interrater and test-retest reliability for anxiety-related disorders (Sheehan et al., 
            2010
         ).
